00:07:15.430 --> 00:07:21.790
So let's get into a
brief history of guitar.

00:07:21.790 --> 00:07:23.660
Guitar, the earliest
predecessors

00:07:23.660 --> 00:07:29.060
are actually quite ancient, from
Asia thousands of years ago.

00:07:29.060 --> 00:07:31.550
But one distinction
about these instruments

00:07:31.550 --> 00:07:34.960
is that they were carved
out of a block of wood.

00:07:34.960 --> 00:07:36.000
The body of it.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:38.750
So you took a log or
a big piece of wood

00:07:38.750 --> 00:07:41.700
and just start hacking
at it, creating a cavity.

00:07:41.700 --> 00:07:43.910
And you glue a
soundboard over that.

00:07:43.910 --> 00:07:46.650
And you could still
have frets back then.

00:07:46.650 --> 00:07:49.270
These were usually made
out of tendon or something,

00:07:49.270 --> 00:07:52.390
and they're tied
around the neck.

00:07:52.390 --> 00:07:57.390
And this is really the
earliest form of guitar.

00:07:57.390 --> 00:08:01.980
But we start talking about
used instruments today,

00:08:01.980 --> 00:08:04.300
we go into the
[? biwela. ?] That's

00:08:04.300 --> 00:08:09.810
the true old guitar starting
from the Renaissance

00:08:09.810 --> 00:08:11.880
and Baroque periods.

00:08:11.880 --> 00:08:14.070
And in this instrument,
what we have

00:08:14.070 --> 00:08:17.420
is a body that's created
from thin plates of wood

00:08:17.420 --> 00:08:21.520
that were actually bent to
create the form of the sides.

00:08:21.520 --> 00:08:24.910
The back was glued on, and
it's much, much lighter

00:08:24.910 --> 00:08:27.840
than an instrument that was
carved out of a chunk of wood.

00:08:27.840 --> 00:08:30.910
Acoustically, it behaves
much different in how

00:08:30.910 --> 00:08:35.610
it vibrates and responds to
the attack on the strings.

00:08:35.610 --> 00:08:39.000
So this is really where
we start seeing things

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:42.350
that sound more like guitars.

00:08:42.350 --> 00:08:49.790
Now a couple centuries ago,
we have the romantic guitar.

00:08:49.790 --> 00:08:52.820
And it's looking a lot closer
to what guitars look like today.

00:08:52.820 --> 00:08:54.690
You see it's a
little bit narrower.

00:08:57.600 --> 00:08:59.490
Main guitarists at
the time they used

00:08:59.490 --> 00:09:01.570
it, Fernando Sor and Giuliani.

00:09:01.570 --> 00:09:04.610
They're like the
Mozart of the guitar.

00:09:04.610 --> 00:09:08.090
These are the instruments
that they used.

00:09:08.090 --> 00:09:11.040
But the biggest evolution
of the instrument

00:09:11.040 --> 00:09:14.550
was done when a Spaniard
by the name of Antonio

00:09:14.550 --> 00:09:20.670
Torres in the 1850s designed
the guitar that we know today.

00:09:20.670 --> 00:09:23.052
OK, this is the modern
classical guitar.

00:09:23.052 --> 00:09:24.510
There was no
distinction back then,

00:09:24.510 --> 00:09:26.300
it was just the Spanish guitar.

00:09:26.300 --> 00:09:30.450
The body was much wider, and
some very interesting things

00:09:30.450 --> 00:09:35.560
were done internally with the
bracing and the scale length

00:09:35.560 --> 00:09:38.410
to give you the instrument
that we know today.

00:09:38.410 --> 00:09:42.090
So Antonio Torres is
the father of the guitar

00:09:42.090 --> 00:09:45.420
very much like
Antonio Stradivarius

00:09:45.420 --> 00:09:47.800
is the father of the violin.

00:09:47.800 --> 00:09:53.310
And not too much has been
changed as far as the looks

00:09:53.310 --> 00:09:55.840
of the guitar goes.

00:09:55.840 --> 00:09:57.510
Technologically,
though, there have

00:09:57.510 --> 00:10:00.270
been some modern
evolutions of the guitar.

00:10:00.270 --> 00:10:01.940
And if there's time
