00:57:21.784 --> 00:57:22.700
AUDIENCE: I'm curious.

00:57:22.700 --> 00:57:24.595
You use the Japanese
chisels, but you

00:57:24.595 --> 00:57:28.220
use Western planes, which are
pushed rather than pulled.

00:57:28.220 --> 00:57:30.590
And I just wondered if
you tried the pulling one,

00:57:30.590 --> 00:57:34.190
and if there's a difference
in the woodworking style.

00:57:34.190 --> 00:57:37.340
EREZ PERELMAN: Yeah, I
have Japanese planes, too.

00:57:37.340 --> 00:57:39.320
They're a little more
finicky to set up,

00:57:39.320 --> 00:57:43.800
there's no adjusting
rings on them, or screws.

00:57:43.800 --> 00:57:48.230
But the steel is
definitely superior,

00:57:48.230 --> 00:57:53.460
but it comes down to the
tool that does the job best.

00:57:53.460 --> 00:57:56.330
And I find the Western
style adjustments allows

00:57:56.330 --> 00:57:59.102
me to get there with planing.

00:57:59.102 --> 00:58:00.810
With the chisels, it's
a different story.

00:58:00.810 --> 00:58:03.890
I want an edge that's going
to hold as long as possible.

00:58:03.890 --> 00:58:06.430
So I like to use the
Japanese chisels there.

00:58:06.430 --> 00:58:09.130
I have Western chisels that
are great, too, depending

00:58:09.130 --> 00:58:11.090
on the wood I'm cutting.

00:58:11.090 --> 00:58:15.170
A lot of the tools are
specific for a single thing

00:58:15.170 --> 00:58:16.510
that I'm going to use them on.

00:58:16.510 --> 00:58:19.340
So it's really
finding what it's for,

00:58:19.340 --> 00:58:22.490
and then learning how to
do it the best way there.

00:58:22.490 --> 00:58:24.550
AUDIENCE: So as a past
life as a researcher,

00:58:24.550 --> 00:58:26.856
you probably spent a
lot of time thinking

00:58:26.856 --> 00:58:28.860
about how to do new
things in new ways.

00:58:28.860 --> 00:58:34.570
Have you thought about new ways
to do bracing, or double tops,

00:58:34.570 --> 00:58:36.630
and all sorts of
stuff like that?

00:58:36.630 --> 00:58:39.690
EREZ PERELMAN: Yeah,
that's a great question.

00:58:39.690 --> 00:58:41.460
So it's interesting.

00:58:41.460 --> 00:58:45.230
When I first started
building guitar,

00:58:45.230 --> 00:58:49.090
I was convinced I'm going to
invent the best guitar that

00:58:49.090 --> 00:58:52.780
was ever built. And I thought
about it for a long time,

00:58:52.780 --> 00:58:55.100
and I came up with this crazy
design called the prison

00:58:55.100 --> 00:58:56.160
guitar.

00:58:56.160 --> 00:58:58.690
And it was crazy, it was insane.

00:58:58.690 --> 00:59:02.680
It turned out beautiful,
but after years, and years,

00:59:02.680 --> 00:59:08.320
and years, I realized respecting
the tradition, the centuries

00:59:08.320 --> 00:59:11.690
that people tried different
things and what survived,

00:59:11.690 --> 00:59:13.580
there's a lot of things
to learn from that.

00:59:13.580 --> 00:59:14.930
Today, there are double tops.

00:59:14.930 --> 00:59:19.360
Double tops are guitars that are
designed with volume in mind.

00:59:19.360 --> 00:59:21.980
Basically, you take
the soundboard,

00:59:21.980 --> 00:59:24.760
which is a two millimeter
thick piece of wood.

00:59:24.760 --> 00:59:26.790
And how do you make
it even lighter?

00:59:26.790 --> 00:59:29.610
So what they do is they
hollow it out and stick

00:59:29.610 --> 00:59:33.600
something synthetic, it's called
Nomex, in a honeycomb fashion.

00:59:33.600 --> 00:59:38.210
This is coming from aeronautical
and space engineering.

00:59:38.210 --> 00:59:43.240
You can cut that the weight by
half, get a much louder guitar.

00:59:43.240 --> 00:59:46.330
And I've done it, I've
experimented with that.

00:59:46.330 --> 00:59:49.100
But I believe the
quality of sound

00:59:49.100 --> 00:59:53.630
is compromised with
that kind of guitar.

00:59:53.630 --> 00:59:56.170
I'm a very strong
believer in the solid wood

00:59:56.170 --> 00:59:58.327
traditional style of instrument.

00:59:58.327 --> 00:59:59.910
I do I have two
pictures here, though,

00:59:59.910 --> 01:00:01.900
to show some innovation
that has been

01:00:01.900 --> 01:00:03.770
done with traditional guitars.

01:00:03.770 --> 01:00:06.670
These are still
traditional guitars.

01:00:06.670 --> 01:00:10.600
So on the left, you see a
guitar with a hole in the side.

01:00:10.600 --> 01:00:14.080
It's crazy, but it's very
popular today amongst players.

01:00:14.080 --> 01:00:15.840
It's called a sound port.

01:00:15.840 --> 01:00:18.990
What it does is it gives the
player a bit of that sound.

01:00:18.990 --> 01:00:21.170
It's throwing it in their face.

01:00:21.170 --> 01:00:24.700
And this is especially
important for people

01:00:24.700 --> 01:00:26.970
who are playing with a
big orchestra behind them,

01:00:26.970 --> 01:00:29.460
or if you're playing
with an accompaniment.

01:00:29.460 --> 01:00:30.350
A few people.

01:00:30.350 --> 01:00:32.900
And then you really
want to hear yourself,

01:00:32.900 --> 01:00:36.400
so this really gives
you that ability.

01:00:36.400 --> 01:00:38.890
Additionally, it's hard
to make out in that photo.

01:00:38.890 --> 01:00:41.050
It's an elevated fingerboard.

01:00:41.050 --> 01:00:44.800
The fingerboard is raised
above the sound board

01:00:44.800 --> 01:00:47.670
to give you a lot more
access to the higher notes.

01:00:47.670 --> 01:00:50.760
It makes it an
ergonomic feature,

01:00:50.760 --> 01:00:53.450
more comfortable
to play up high.

01:00:53.450 --> 01:00:58.720
The guitar you see on the right
side is a incredible guitar,

01:00:58.720 --> 01:01:00.390
it's called a Brahms guitar.

01:01:00.390 --> 01:01:04.610
One of my favorite players
ever is called Paul Galbraith.

01:01:04.610 --> 01:01:09.380
And he developed this guitar
with the late luthier David

01:01:09.380 --> 01:01:11.430
Rubio from England.

01:01:11.430 --> 01:01:12.980
It's essentially
a guitar that has

01:01:12.980 --> 01:01:17.280
fanned frets where every string
has a different scale length.

01:01:17.280 --> 01:01:20.811
If you notice that the bridge
and the nut are different

01:01:20.811 --> 01:01:21.310
angles.

01:01:21.310 --> 01:01:24.280
So the bass and the trebles
have different lengths.

01:01:24.280 --> 01:01:27.250
And I had to write a
program to compute the scale

01:01:27.250 --> 01:01:31.080
lengths on this guitar, too.

01:01:31.080 --> 01:01:33.570
What's incredible and special
about this instrument,

01:01:33.570 --> 01:01:38.360
normally when you have more
than six strings on a guitar,

01:01:38.360 --> 01:01:39.992
it's extra basses.

01:01:39.992 --> 01:01:42.200
So you add basses, basses,
basses, and it's very easy

01:01:42.200 --> 01:01:43.810
to control them with the thumb.

01:01:43.810 --> 01:01:46.790
It doesn't open up a lot of
the range of the instrument.

01:01:46.790 --> 01:01:49.710
On this guitar, you
actually add a treble.

01:01:49.710 --> 01:01:51.925
So there's one extra
treble, and one extra bass.

01:01:51.925 --> 01:01:54.190
So it's opening it
up from both sides.

01:01:54.190 --> 01:01:56.470
It opens up a whole
new body of music

01:01:56.470 --> 01:02:00.640
that couldn't be played on the
guitar before to be played.

01:02:00.640 --> 01:02:02.525
It is a difficult
instrument to play.

01:02:02.525 --> 01:02:04.550
You play it upright
like a cello,

01:02:04.550 --> 01:02:08.520
it has an end pin that
goes in the floor.

01:02:08.520 --> 01:02:10.320
So to answer your
question, there

01:02:10.320 --> 01:02:14.250
is experimentation
within tradition.

01:02:14.250 --> 01:02:16.360
And today, I continue
experimenting.

01:02:16.360 --> 01:02:18.320
But my experiments
are much more focused

01:02:18.320 --> 01:02:22.070
on tenth of a millimeter thing.

01:02:22.070 --> 01:02:24.460
Very, very fine adjustments.

01:02:24.460 --> 01:02:28.040
Where I'm looking for something
very consistent, but to improve

01:02:28.040 --> 01:02:29.700
it and finding
which way to wiggle

01:02:29.700 --> 01:02:33.760
the curve to achieve finer
and finer instruments.

01:02:33.760 --> 01:02:38.880
Also to a lesser extent,
but just as important,

01:02:38.880 --> 01:02:40.490
I have clients
with special needs.

01:02:40.490 --> 01:02:42.540
For example, clients
that have injuries

01:02:42.540 --> 01:02:44.740
in their backs or shoulders.

01:02:44.740 --> 01:02:49.020
And one of them asked for
an adjustable support system

01:02:49.020 --> 01:02:52.090
with a guitar that
could lay on the floor,

01:02:52.090 --> 01:02:54.170
and could be angled and
raised to any angles.

01:02:54.170 --> 01:02:55.390
You can even stand with it.

01:02:55.390 --> 01:02:58.590
So here I built him
a special support

01:02:58.590 --> 01:03:00.750
system out of a monopod.

01:03:00.750 --> 01:03:04.110
Basically like a camera monopod.

01:03:04.110 --> 01:03:10.750
And that's one of the
benefits of-- you're

01:03:10.750 --> 01:03:12.755
building every guitar
for the client,

01:03:12.755 --> 01:03:15.130
and it might encompass something
like this in the support

01:03:15.130 --> 01:03:17.710
systems, too, specifically
for their needs.

01:03:17.710 --> 01:03:19.920
I don't do a cookie
cutter approach

01:03:19.920 --> 01:03:23.750
where everything is exactly
the same, take it or leave it.

01:03:23.750 --> 01:03:26.470
So it's a very feedback
oriented process.

01:03:26.470 --> 01:03:33.190
And the research is done within
a very controlled manner.

01:03:33.190 --> 01:03:36.160
AUDIENCE: Did you get a
chance to look at the work

01:03:36.160 --> 01:03:40.390
that Adrian Houtsma
did-- like in 1975,

01:03:40.390 --> 01:03:43.564
80-- on guitar acoustics?

01:03:43.564 --> 01:03:45.230
EREZ PERELMAN: The
name sounds familiar.

01:03:45.230 --> 01:03:48.120
I used to read a lot of
the-- is it GAO publications?

01:03:51.050 --> 01:03:54.610
Did he do the round bracing?

01:03:54.610 --> 01:03:56.320
The circle bracing?

01:03:56.320 --> 01:03:57.760
AUDIENCE: The bridge support.

01:03:57.760 --> 01:03:59.220
EREZ PERELMAN: Bridge support.

01:03:59.220 --> 01:04:01.110
AUDIENCE: It was
basically, you can

01:04:01.110 --> 01:04:05.420
make the face a
little thinner if you

01:04:05.420 --> 01:04:08.450
prevent the bridge from rotating
with a separate support.

01:04:08.450 --> 01:04:09.750
EREZ PERELMAN: Yeah.

01:04:09.750 --> 01:04:12.110
Specifically, no, I don't
remember his research.

01:04:12.110 --> 01:04:16.620
But every builder
researches to some extent.

01:04:16.620 --> 01:04:18.470
A lot more here in
America, for some reason.

01:04:18.470 --> 01:04:21.180
It's the land of cowboys here.

01:04:21.180 --> 01:04:26.490
And it's very interesting to
see what people are doing.

01:04:26.490 --> 01:04:31.550
Again, I'm a very strong
proponent of the traditional

01:04:31.550 --> 01:04:36.470
build, for the special reason
that I had the opportunity

01:04:36.470 --> 01:04:38.890
to play those guitars
made by Torres.

01:04:38.890 --> 01:04:41.620
This is a very rare opportunity.

01:04:41.620 --> 01:04:44.980
If anyone plays guitar
here and they have a chance

01:04:44.980 --> 01:04:48.670
to play a historic instrument,
the sound is really magical.

01:04:48.670 --> 01:04:52.140
And it's impossible to
portray it on recording.

01:04:52.140 --> 01:04:56.060
You really have to try
it out to appreciate it.

01:04:56.060 --> 01:05:00.620
So I'm open minded, I'm
always considering new things.

01:05:00.620 --> 01:05:03.240
But to me, the
ideal sound is still

01:05:03.240 --> 01:05:05.850
coming from that
traditional design.

01:05:05.850 --> 01:05:08.590
And I'll always look for better.

01:05:08.590 --> 01:05:11.114
But right now, that's
the ideal for me.

01:05:11.114 --> 01:05:13.030
AUDIENCE: If it's public,
how many instruments

01:05:13.030 --> 01:05:15.316
do you build it every year?

01:05:15.316 --> 01:05:16.940
EREZ PERELMAN: Sure,
it's very limited.

01:05:16.940 --> 01:05:20.840
Each guitar takes me
over a month to build.

01:05:20.840 --> 01:05:25.180
So I'm building around
10 to 12 guitars.

01:05:25.180 --> 01:05:30.350
And this is generally the
output of luthiers doing guitars

01:05:30.350 --> 01:05:36.210
at the top level without trying
to expand and scale the shop

01:05:36.210 --> 01:05:39.100
with helpers, or big machines.

01:05:39.100 --> 01:05:41.100
So I'm not trying to
build more guitars,

01:05:41.100 --> 01:05:44.630
I'm trying to improve
the quality of each one.

01:05:44.630 --> 01:05:46.350
And the French
polish, as I said,

01:05:46.350 --> 01:05:50.560
that takes a huge amount of
time in the build process.

01:05:50.560 --> 01:05:54.560
So that limits how many
guitars you can make.

